      <div id="mainContent" class="main column clearfix"> 
       <h1> At Reagan Conference, Cadet Assistants Work, Learn – and Network</h1>
       <div class="alignRight newsimagelarge">
        <img src="/uploadedImages/_VMI/Communications_Marketing/Newscenter/Headlines/Headline_Images/13-14/ReaganConfLuncheon2015JRR0058Fulltext.jpg" alt="FullTextImage/img/@alt" class="bordered">
        <span class="caption">Adams Center assistants Salena Chiep and Austin Baje talk with conference participants at the Monday luncheon. – VMI Photos by John Robertson IV.</span>
       </div>
       <p>LEXINGTON, Va., Nov. 4, 2014 – It’s been a whirlwind two days for Salena Chiep ’16 and Austin Bajc ’17, cadet assistants at the John A. Adams ’71 Center for Military History and Strategic Analysis, as a conference on the foreign policy legacy of former President Ronald Reagan wraps up – but both agreed that the gathering has been an invaluable learning experience.<br><br>Chiep, an international studies major, found herself with butterflies in her stomach when she learned she’d be acting as personal assistant to retired Navy Adm. James Stavridis, who served as NATO supreme allied commander Europe from 2009 to 2013. Those nerves vanished, though, once she met the admiral.<br><br>“He’s a great guy and very personable,” said Chiep of Stavridis, who addressed an audience in Gillis Theater Monday on challenges and opportunities for international security in the 21st century.</p>
       <p>In advance of the conference, titled “The Enduring Legacy: Leadership and National Security Affairs During the Ronald Reagan Era,” Chiep created the time line of major events during the Reagan administration to be included in the program and a similar one to be posted on the Adams Center’s Facebook page announcing the conference.</p>
       <div class="well">
        <a title="Related story: VMI Professors Speak on Missteps in Reagan's Foreign Policy" href="#History">Related story: VMI Professors Speak on Missteps in Reagan's Foreign Policy</a>
       </div>
       <p>Bajc, a history major, had assignments for the conference that may have had a lower profile, but were just as important.</p>
       <p>“I handled all of the permits for the Corps of Cadets so they could attend these panels and miss class,” explained Bajc. More than 300 cadets attended some portion of the conference.<br><br>Bajc, who plans to commission in the Army upon graduation from VMI, cheerfully described himself as “the go-to guy” during the gathering, filling in wherever needed. <br><br>This morning, one of his major responsibilities was storing luggage for out-of-town guests so they could check out of their hotels before coming to post for the final day of the conference.<br><br>Both cadets said they were grateful that their duties didn’t prevent them from chatting with conference participants from a variety of backgrounds, or attending the many panels offered over the past two days.<br><br>“All of the speeches have been great,” said Chiep, “but the best part of this entire conference has been the opportunity to meet so many different people. The networking opportunities we’ve had have been incredible.”<br><br>Bajc said that he’d most enjoyed “looking at the Reagan administration and drawing conclusions for today.”<br><br>He continued, “I just came from a panel on the Middle East, and there’s so many connections there [between the Reagan administration’s approach to problems and those taken by the U.S. government today]. We’re fitting a lot of things into a global problem when maybe looking at things through a regional lens would be a better idea.”<br><br>Basc also praised the speech given last night by Jack F. Matlock Jr., former U.S. ambassador to the Soviet Union.<br><br>“The Cold War wasn’t really won by anyone,” said Basc in recounting Matlock’s speech. “It was more of a collaborative effort between the U.S. and the Soviets to end the Cold War together.”<br><br>Like Bajc, Chiep said that she’d enjoyed learning more about an era that occurred before she or any of her fellow cadets were born.<br><br>“The Reagan administration had a great effect on politics today,” said Chiep, who plans to commission in the Marine Corps upon graduation. “It’s been great learning how Cold War history connects to history today.”<br><br>The conference, it seems, has only stirred up a desire to keep learning – and perhaps to participate in similar gatherings in the future.<br><br>“It’s been a great experience working with Lt. Col. [Brad] Coleman and the [Center for Leadership and Ethics] and everyone who’ s been involved,” said Chiep. “I have great hopes for any future conferences we have and the people we’ll be working with.”<br><br>Coleman, director of the Adams Center and associate professor of history at VMI, had high praise for his assistants.<br><br>“They’re outstanding young people,” he said.</p>
       <hr>
       <h1><a id="History" title="History" name="History">‘Learn That History’</a></h1>
       <p class="sub-header-italic">VMI Professors Speak on Missteps in Reagan’s Foreign Policy</p>
       <p>LEXINGTON, Va., Nov. 4, 2014 – Two VMI faculty members were among the panelists giving presentations during “The Enduring Legacy: Leadership and National Security During the Ronald Reagan Era,” held on the VMI post Nov. 3-4. <br><br>Brig. Gen. Charles F. Brower IV and Col. James Hentz, both professors of international studies, gave papers in a session titled, “Reagan in the World: The Middle East and Africa.”<br><br>Brower, who served as Army aide to Reagan from 1982 to 1984, gave a talk titled, “Stranger in a Dangerous Land: Reagan and Lebanon, 1981-1984.” In his remarks, Brower argued that then-President Reagan’s missteps in Lebanon in the early 1980s were the direct result of Reagan’s viewing a regional conflict through a Cold War lens.<br><br>For Brower, the memories of the bombing of the U.S. Marine Corps barracks in Beirut, Lebanon, on Oct. 23, 1983, are as fresh as if the event had occurred yesterday – for it was he who received the call from Robert McFarland, national security adviser, shortly after 2 a.m. that fateful Sunday morning. <br><br>It was Brower’s grave and grim assignment to awaken the president so McFarland and Secretary of State George C. Shultz could inform the chief executive of the attack that killed 241 American servicemen.<br><br>“Reagan was ashen-faced and in a state of disbelief,” said Brower, who recalled that Reagan later referred to that October Sunday as “the saddest day of my life.”<br><br>Unknowingly, the Reagan administration had stepped into a simmering cauldron of ethnic and religious tensions fueled not only by the Lebanese themselves, but also the Soviet-armed Syrians and the Israelis, anxious to protect their own territory and interests. By February 1984, the multi-national peacekeeping force that had included the U.S. troops was withdrawn from Lebanon.<br><br>“Lebanon is a harsh teacher,” Brower noted. In a letter to columnist William F. Buckley in December 1983, Reagan wrote, “The Middle East is a complicated place. Well, not really a place, a state of mind – a disordered mind.”<br><br>Like his colleague Brower, Hentz elaborated on the missteps Reagan took by looking at regional conflicts through a global lens. Hentz’s talk, “United States Southern Africa Policy Under Reagan: The Specter of Colonialism,” began by pointing out that the Reagan administration’s approach of “constructive engagement” with Africa was anything but constructive.<br><br>Anxious to stop the spread of communism, Reagan treated Africa as its colonial handlers had done, Hentz argued, with a paternalistic approach, and was fearful of its socialist governments.<br><br>“U.S. foreign policy over time conflated communism with the Soviet Union, and one of the themes of this talk is, ‘They’re not the same thing,’” said Hentz. <br><br>“We conflated an ideology with the interests of a state, and we continue to make that mistake today. … A master narrative dominating the regional narrative is a recurrent problem in U.S. foreign policy, and we need to learn that history.”<br><br>The conference, the first of its kind offered at VMI, was sponsored by the John A. Adams ’71 Center for Military History and Strategic Analysis and the VMI Center for Leadership and Ethics.</p>
       <p><em>-Mary Price</em></p>
       <p align="center">&nbsp;-VMI-</p> 
